        </div>
        
        <div class="doi">
            <p>doi: 10.1234/arxiv.2024.0892345</p>
            <p>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/s00134-024-07891-x">https://doi.org/10.1007/s00134-024-07891-x</a></p>
            <p><a href="https://doi.org/10.1038/s41586-023-04567-2">https://doi.org/10.1038/s41586-023-04567-2</a></p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="abstract">
            <h2>Abstract</h2>
            <p>This survey presents a comprehensive overview of attention mechanisms in deep neural networks, covering their theoretical foundations, architectural variants, and applications across natural language processing, computer vision, and speech recognition.</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="keywords">
            <p><strong>Keywords:</strong> attention, deep learning, neural networks, transformer, self-attention, multi-head attention, NLP, computer vision</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="submitted-date">
            <p>Submitted 15 Jan 2026 (v1), last revised 28 Feb 2026 (this version, v2)</p>
            <p class="categories"><strong>Categories:</strong> cs.LG, cs.CL, cs.CV; I.2.6; I.2.7</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="section">
            <h2>1. Introduction</h2>
            <p>Attention mechanisms have revolutionized the field of deep learning, enabling models to focus on relevant parts of input data<sup>[1,2]</sup>. Originally introduced in the context of neural machine translation<sup>[3]</sup>, attention has since become a fundamental component in state-of-the-art models across various domains.</p>
            <p>The transformer architecture<sup>[4]</sup>, based entirely on self-attention mechanisms, has achieved remarkable success in natural language processing tasks. Its ability to capture long-range dependencies without recurrent processing has made it the backbone of modern language models.</p>
        </div>
        
